    <button onclick="showTab('trends')" class="px-4 py-2 bg-indigo-600 text-white rounded-full">Periodic Trends</button>
  </div>

  <!-- Content -->
  <main class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 space-y-6 mb-12">

    <section id="stoichiometry" class="content-section">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2 text-indigo-700">Stoichiometry</h2>
      <p>Stoichiometry is the calculation of reactants and products in chemical reactions based on the law of conservation of mass.</p>
      <h3 class="font-semibold mt-4">Example:</h3>
      <pre class="bg-gray-100 p-2 rounded mt-2 text-sm">N₂ + 3H₂ → 2NH₃</pre>
      <ul class="list-disc ml-6 mt-2">
        <li>1 mole of nitrogen reacts with 3 moles of hydrogen to produce 2 moles of ammonia</li>
        <li>Mole ratios are used to convert between quantities of substances</li>
        <li>Used for determining limiting reagents, theoretical yields, and percent yields</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="equilibrium" class="content-section hidden">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2 text-indigo-700">Chemical Equilibrium</h2>
      <p>A dynamic state where forward and reverse reaction rates are equal, resulting in no net change in concentrations over time.</p>
      <ul class="list-disc ml-6 mt-2">
        <li><strong>Equilibrium constant (K):</strong> K = [Products]/[Reactants]</li>
        <li><strong>Le Chatelier’s Principle:</strong> System shifts to counteract stress</li>
        <li><strong>Reaction Quotient (Q):</strong> Predicts direction before equilibrium</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="atomic" class="content-section hidden">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2 text-indigo-700">Atomic Structure & Orbitals</h2>
      <p>Atoms consist of protons, neutrons, and electrons. Electrons occupy orbitals around the nucleus.</p>
      <ul class="list-disc ml-6 mt-2">
        <li><strong>Protons:</strong> Positive charge, in the nucleus</li>
        <li><strong>Neutrons:</strong> Neutral charge, also in the nucleus</li>
        <li><strong>Electrons:</strong> Negative charge, found in orbitals</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="trends" class="content-section hidden">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2 text-indigo-700">Periodic Trends</h2>
      <p>Patterns in element properties across the periodic table.</p>
      <ul class="list-disc ml-6 mt-2">
        <li><strong>Atomic Radius:</strong> Decreases across a period, increases down a group</li>
        <li><strong>Ionic Radius:</strong> Depends on cation/anion status</li>
        <li><strong>Ionization Energy:</strong> Increases across a period</li>
        <li><strong>Electronegativity:</strong> Increases across a period</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

  </main>

  <!-- Footer -->
  <footer class="bg-indigo-600 text-white text-center py-4">
    <p>© Chemistry Education | Learn the fundamentals of chemistry</p>
